-- Spanish Two-Year Notes Stay Higher After First Bill Sale Since Downgrade
-- B y   L u c y   M e a k i n
-- 2012-01-17T09:56:08Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2012-01-17/spanish-two-year-notes-stay-higher-after-first-bill-sale-since-downgrade.html
Spanish two-year notes stayed higher
after borrowing costs fell at its first bill sale since the
nation’s credit rating was downgraded by  Standard & Poor’s .  Spain ’s two-year note yield was 11 basis lower at 2.88
percent as of 9:48 a.m. London time. The nation’s 10-year bond
yield fell nine basis points to 5.09 percent.  Spain sold 4.88 billion of 12-month and 18-month bills,
compared with the maximum target of 5 billion euros it had set
for the sale.  It sold the 12-month bills at an average yield of 2.049
percent, compared to 4.05 percent the last time the securities
were sold on Dec. 13. The average yield on the 18-month notes
was 2.399 percent, compared with 4.226 percent in December.  To contact the reporter on this story:
